docs.snippet: Alex Eaton-Salners is back with a tough Thursday.
docs.lead_paragraph: THURSDAY PUZZLE — You have to admire people who find their niche almost right away and stick with it, particularly when they are so good at what they do. The constructor Alex Eaton-Salners has made a name for himself as a Thursday constructor, and his puzzles usually have some neat twist to them.

docs.abstract: Faye Driscoll’s trilogy has explored the relationship between performer and spectators. In Part 3 she asks for assistance.
docs.snippet: Faye Driscoll’s trilogy has explored the relationship between performer and spectators. In Part 3 she asks for assistance.
docs.lead_paragraph: The very first thing that the choreographer Faye Driscoll does in “Thank You for Coming: Space,” the final installment in a trilogy, is act out the series’s title. Standing in a slouch, barefoot in a T-shirt and jeans, she thanks her audience for showing up, acknowledging the quotidian difficulties of attending live performance. The speech is disarming, but also, as it extends in awkward silences and tangents, a little disturbing. Something is off.

headline.main: Review: A Choreographer Alone With Her Audience and Death
headline.print_headline: A Choreographer Alone With Her Audience and Death

docs.abstract: This warm documentary uses one woman’s singular passion to fuel a tale of zoological discovery, blatant sexism and environmental alarm.
docs.snippet: This warm documentary uses one woman’s singular passion to fuel a tale of zoological discovery, blatant sexism and environmental alarm.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the summer of 1956, years before Jane Goodall encountered her chimpanzees, a young Canadian biologist named Anne Innis Dagg traveled, alone, to South Africa to meet her favorite beast in its natural habitat. As documented in “The Woman Who Loves Giraffes,” that trip — aside from a Scottish study of red deer — would make her the first scientist ever to study the behavior of animals in the wild. She was 23.

headline.main: ‘The Woman Who Loves Giraffes’ Review: Crackers for Animals
headline.print_headline: A Special Spot  In Her Heart

docs.abstract: In the documentaries “Peshmerga” and “The Battle of Mosul,” Bernard-Henri Lévy offers a portrait of the fighters trying to repel the Islamic State.
docs.snippet: In the documentaries “Peshmerga” and “The Battle of Mosul,” Bernard-Henri Lévy offers a portrait of the fighters trying to repel the Islamic State.
docs.lead_paragraph: Although he supplies a running narration, the French intellectual Bernard-Henri Lévy steps in front of the camera only occasionally in “Peshmerga” and “The Battle of Mosul,” and that is mostly to the benefit of this pair of documentaries he directed. “Peshmerga,” the longer of the two, aims to put faces on the Kurdish soldiers fighting the Islamic State in Iraqi Kurdistan, a region where conflicts have a tendency to dissolve into a blur of headlines and abstractions.

headline.main: Review: Two Battle Diaries From Iraq

docs.abstract: We focused on nonvoters and infrequent ones before the 2018 midterm elections and saw astonishing results.
docs.snippet: We focused on nonvoters and infrequent ones before the 2018 midterm elections and saw astonishing results.
docs.lead_paragraph: Since Donald Trump’s election in 2016, the left has obsessed over which voters to mobilize and how to do so. One camp wants to concentrate on moderate white voters. Another says white suburban women are the key to victory in 2020. Yet what may be the most effective use of resources is to reach out to a group of voters few strategists are talking about: infrequent voters, who are disproportionately women, people of color and young people.

headline.main: What if Democrats Tried Real Outreach?
headline.print_headline: The Voters Democrats Fail to See

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A sharply divided House voted on Thursday to force President Trump to come to Congress for authorization before taking further military action against Iran, in a sharp response to his ratcheting up of hostilities with Tehran without the explicit approval of the legislative branch.

docs.abstract: Five inmates were slain last week, and two inmates escaped. The violence has illuminated an understaffed system troubled by gang warfare.
docs.snippet: Five inmates were slain last week, and two inmates escaped. The violence has illuminated an understaffed system troubled by gang warfare.
docs.lead_paragraph: JACKSON, Miss. — Betty Turner dreaded what her son would face in the state penitentiary in Parchman, the Mississippi Delta prison that has, over the course of more than a century, earned a dark and near-mythic reputation for cruelty and institutional racism. Her fears were realized when he described meals of just a slice of bologna with a packet of mustard, sightings of rats and mold, and nights spent on a mat on a cold, damp floor.

headline.main: ‘A Blood Bath’: 5 Dead as Gang Violence Rocks Mississippi Prisons
headline.print_headline: ‘An Undeniable Crisis’: Gang Violence Rocks Prisons in Mississippi

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senator Mike Lee of Utah, a libertarian-leaning Republican, has always been a loud but lonely voice in his party clamoring to rein in presidential war powers, so it came as little surprise on Wednesday when he questioned President Trump’s decision to strike Iran’s most important general.
